description:
In lichen_l2.c:443-456 (enable path) and lichen_l2.c:656-662 (iface_init), identical link_ctx initialization logic is duplicated:

```c
// In enable (lines 443-457):
if (!atomic_get(&link_ctx_initialized)) {
    const uint8_t *eui64 = lichen_lora_l2_get_eui64();
    if (eui64 == NULL) { ... }
    secure_zero(&link_ctx, sizeof(link_ctx));
    lichen_link_init(&link_ctx, eui64);
    atomic_set(&link_ctx_initialized, 1);
}

// In iface_init (lines 655-662):
lichen_link_init(&link_ctx, eui64);
atomic_set(&link_ctx_initialized, 1);
```

The comment in enable explains why extraction is avoided (mutex considerations), and this is a defensible choice. However, the iface_init path is missing the secure_zero() call that enable has. This creates an inconsistency where enable defensively zeros before init, but iface_init does not.

What goes wrong: If lichen_link_init() does not zero all fields (relying on caller to provide clean memory), stale data could persist in the init path but not the enable path - inconsistent security posture.

Suggested fix: Either add secure_zero() to iface_init for consistency, or document that lichen_link_init() guarantees full zeroing.
